docs.abstract: The state became one of the first to make major changes in police practices in the wake of George Floyd’s killing, which has spurred nationwide protests.
docs.snippet: The state became one of the first to make major changes in police practices in the wake of George Floyd’s killing, which has spurred nationwide protests.
docs.lead_paragraph: New York on Friday became one of the first states to take meaningful action to restrict police forces after the killing of George Floyd, banning the use of chokeholds by law enforcement and repealing a half-century-old law that has kept police disciplinary records secret in the state.

headline.main: N.Y. Bans Chokeholds and Approves Other Measures to Restrict Police
headline.print_headline: New York State Moves to Check Police Conduct

docs.abstract: Dwindling white support for the president leads to a deficit of at least six points in each state.
docs.snippet: Dwindling white support for the president leads to a deficit of at least six points in each state.
docs.lead_paragraph: President Trump has lost significant ground in the six battleground states that clinched his Electoral College victory in 2016, according to New York Times/Siena College surveys, with Joseph R. Biden Jr. opening double-digit leads in Michigan, Pennsylvania and Wisconsin.

headline.main: In Poll, Trump Falls Far Behind Biden in Six Key Battleground States
headline.print_headline: Biden Gains Lead in Key States As Trump Loses White Voters

docs.abstract: Statues and monuments that have long honored racist figures are being boxed up, spray-painted — or beheaded.
docs.snippet: Statues and monuments that have long honored racist figures are being boxed up, spray-painted — or beheaded.
docs.lead_paragraph: The statues have stood for more than a century in some places. Some are cast in bronze, others carved in stone. And all over the world, as protests against racism and police violence have renewed attention on legacies of injustices, people have been asking: Does this statue still need to be here?

headline.main: How Statues Are Falling Around the World
headline.print_headline: Dumped, Painted, Toppled, Boxed Up and Hoisted Away

docs.abstract: The pianist and “Late Show” bandleader has been bringing musical wake-up calls to events across New York.
docs.snippet: The pianist and “Late Show” bandleader has been bringing musical wake-up calls to events across New York.
docs.lead_paragraph: Jon Batiste, the jazz pianist and “The Late Show With Stephen Colbert” bandleader, has spent the last three weekends marching in the streets of New York, leading musicians and protesters through hymns and songs like “We Shall Overcome” and “Down by the Riverside.” Those without a horn or drum sing and, at Mr. Batiste’s exhortation, say their names: George Floyd. Breonna Taylor. And many others.

headline.main: Jazz Is Built for Protests. Jon Batiste Is Taking It to the Streets.
headline.print_headline: Jon Batiste  Is Taking It To the Streets

docs.abstract: Our culture writers offer suggestions for what to watch or listen to, and how to celebrate Juneteenth.
docs.snippet: Our culture writers offer suggestions for what to watch or listen to, and how to celebrate Juneteenth.
docs.lead_paragraph: On June 19, 1865, news of the Emancipation Proclamation finally reached enslaved African-Americans in Galveston, Texas, more than two years after Abraham Lincoln had signed the document. The day became known as Juneteenth, or Freedom Day, and its celebrations over the years have centered on community, education and food. On Friday, the Schomburg Center for Research in Black Culture in Manhattan commemorates its legacy with “Juneteenth: Creating Legacy in Contested Places,” which interprets the cultural contributions of formerly enslaved African-Americans in their quest for freedom — not only from slavery, but from the limitations placed on their artistic freedoms.
